<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-803-660  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 803 660.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  August 27 1990 v4 n31 p7(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>HHS' medical malpractice data bank draws fire from GAO, Congress.andO;(the US Department of Health and Human Services is criticized bythe General Accounting Office)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rivenbark, Leigh.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A General Accounting Office (GAO) report criticizes the US Healthand Human Services (HHS) medical malpractice data bank and allegesmanagement problems and potential cost overruns.andP;  The report wasdelivered to Congress but has not been made public.andP;  Sourcesfamiliar with it say concerns are raised about procurementprocedures at the Health Resources and Services Administration(HRSA), as well as security and confidentiality issues.andP;  HHS wasrequired by Congress in 1986 to create a data bank with records ondoctors and dentists against whom malpractice suits had beenfiled, disciplinary actions by licensing boards had beeninitiated, or adverse actions by clinical privilege boards orprofessional societies had been taken.andP;  Hospitals are required toquery the data bank every two years and whenever a job applicantis considered.andP;  Unisys began working on the system in Jan 1989 aspart of a five-year, $15.9 million contract; concerns about thesystem are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data BasesHealth CareHospitalGovernment AgencyNational GovernmentPurchasing SystemsReportsUnited States. General Accounting OfficeUnited States. Department of Health and Human ServicesMedical personnel.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>